Mongol () is a 2007 semi-historical war film directed by Sergei Bodrov. The storyline was conceived from a screenplay written by Bodrov and Arif Aliev. Producers for the film comprised Bodrov, Sergei Selyanov and Anton Melnik. The film is based on the early life of Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin, who later came to be known as Genghis Khan. Actors Tadanobu Asano, Sun Honglei and Khulan Chuluun star in principal roles. It is the first motion picture in a trilogy based on his rule over the Mongol Empire.1 The first premiere of the film took place on July 31, 2007.2 Mongol explores abduction, kinship and the repercussions of war.3
The film was an intergovernmental co-production between companies in Germany, Kazakhstan, Mongolia and Russia. Filming took place, for the most part, in the People's Republic of China, principally Inner Mongolia (the Mongol autonomous region), and in Kazakhstan. Shooting began in September 2005, and was completed in November 2006. It was commercially distributed by Picturehouse Entertainment theatrically, and by Universal Studios Home Entertainment for home media. Following its release in theaters, the film was nominated for the 2007 Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film as a submission from Kazakhstan.4 On July 29, 2008, the Original Motion Picture Soundtrack was released by the Varese Sarabande label. The film score was composed by musician Tuomas Kantelinen.
Mongol premiered in theaters in wide release in Russia on September 20, 2007. It opened in the United States in limited release on June 6, 2008 grossing $5,705,761 in domestic ticket sales. It earned $20,821,749 in business through international release to top out at a combined $26,527,510 in gross revenue. The film was technically considered a minor financial success after its theatrical run, and was generally met with positive critical reviews before its initial screening in cinemas. The second installment of the trilogy, provisionally titled The Great Khan, entered pre-production in 2008 and was planned for a cinematic release in 2010.56
Plot
Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin (Tadanobu Asano) as a prisoner in the Tangut kingdom, conveys his memories about his earlier life through a series of flashbacks.
Embarking on an expedition as a young boy, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin (Odnyam Odsuren) is accompanied by his father Yes&lt;U+00FC&gt;gei (Ba Sen) to select a girl as his future wife. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin meets and chooses B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte (Bayertsetseg Erdenebat), although his father wishes him to choose a mate from the Merkit tribe. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin convinces his father to allow him to choose B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte. He promises to return after five years to marry her. On their way home, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin's father is poisoned by an enemy tribe. As he lies dying, he tells Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin that he is now Khan. However, one of his father's warriors, Targutai (Amadu Mamadakov), orders the other tribesmen to loot the dead Khan's camp. Targutai spares Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin's life, declaring a Mongol does not kill children. After falling through the ice of a frozen lake, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is found lying down in the snow by a young boy called Jamukha (Amarbold Tuvshinbayar). The two quickly become friends and perform a traditional ceremony declaring themselves blood brothers. Targutai later captures Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin, holding him in captivity. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin however, escapes late one night and roams the countryside. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is later seen again as a young man (Tadanobu Asano) in 1186. He once again is apprehended by Targutai, who wishes to kill him now that he is grown. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin escapes a second time finding B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte (Khulan Chuluun), and brings her back to his family. Later that night, they are attacked by the Merkit tribe led by Chiledu (Sai Xing Ga), since Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin's father had years before stolen his wife from one of their tribesmen. While being chased on horseback, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is shot with an arrow. B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte whips the horse which Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is on, telling it to go home. B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte is captured by the Merkit leader, as Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin returns safely to his family.7
Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin goes to his childhood friend Jamukha (Sun Honglei), who is now a Khan himself. Jamukha agrees to help him get his wife back and attack the Merkit tribe, though only after a year passes. The attack on the Merkit tribe is a success, and Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin finds B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte alive and Chiledu dead. However, just as he feared, Bort&lt;U+00EB&gt; has already been raped and left pregnant with Chiledu's son, who Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin takes as his own. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin and his men leave early the next morning, and two of Jamukha's soldiers choose to join Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin because he distributes more plunder to his warriors than Jamukha. Jamukha chases down Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin, but Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin refuses to send back Jamukha's combatants and horses because he explains a Mongol warrior is free to choose his leader. Jamukha warns him that his actions will lead to future conflict. Taichar (Bu Ren), Jamukha's brother, is later killed while attempting to steal back Jamukha's horses; Jamukha and Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin go to war. Outnumbered, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin's army is quickly defeated. Jamukha declares victory and decides to make Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin a slave rather than execute him.8
Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is sold to a Tangut Garrison Chief (Zhang Jiong), despite the dire warning given to the man by a Buddhist monk (Ben Hon Sun) acting as his advisor. While imprisoned, the monk pleads with Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin to save his monastery when he is set free sometime in the future. In exchange for delivering a bone fragment to B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte indicating that he is still alive, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin agrees. To get to Tangut, B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte becomes a merchant's concubine, bearing a daughter along the way. Once B&lt;U+00F6&gt;rte arrives in Tangut, she abandons the merchant and bribes the guard for the key to Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin's cell. Once freed, he gathers an army to unify all of the Mongols. In 1196, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin declares war over Jamukha. By 1206, Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin defeats Jamukha (though he sets him free), while Targutai is killed by his own soldiers while attempting to flee the battle. Tem&lt;U+00FC&gt;jin is subsequently designated the Khan of all the Mongols&lt;U+2013&gt;Genghis Khan of the Great Steppe.9
